<br>
The winner of the popular vote in each US House of Representative district receives the electoral vote for that district.  The overall winner of the popular vote in the state of Maine receives the two electoral votes designated for the US Senate.<br>
<br>
In heavily populated states, such as Texas, the electoral votes would be split much more evenly due to the demographics of the congressional districts.  There are areas which are very heavily Republican (Houston, Dallas, and the panhandle area), and other areas which are extremely heavy Democrat (Austin, San Antonio, and El Paso area).  Most of the districts are very heavily weighted to one party or the other. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=truthreason>TruthReason</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm actually Goanad.</span><br>  Posts: 1096<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/25/03 3:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=58.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: No wonder he had to cheat to get into office</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Could it be that 39 states vote Democrat, and the big 11 vote Republican. So the 39 Democratic states would just have to bite it ? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
